---
title: Tool Wrapper Skill
version: 1.0
created: 2026-03-19
status: draft
---

# VISION
Give an AI agent on-demand expertise for a specific library, framework, or API.
Instead of hardcoding conventions in a system prompt, package them here and load this document only when the agent works with that technology.

Goal: reduce prompt bloat, keep conventions version-controlled, share across team.

# CONTEXT
Pattern: Tool Wrapper
Use when: the user is building, reviewing, or debugging code that relies on a specific library.
Trigger keywords: library name, framework name, specific API name.

The agent loads this document when those keywords appear. Context is only consumed when relevant.

Constraints:
- Conventions file must be in `references/` directory
- Rules in the conventions file are treated as absolute truth
- Agent must cite the specific rule when flagging a violation

# STRUCTURE
## File Layout
```
skills/your-library-expert/
  pattern-tool-wrapper.mrcf   ← this file (the skill definition)
  references/
    conventions.md             ← library-specific rules and best practices
```

## Conventions File Format
`references/conventions.md` should contain:
- Naming conventions
- Import patterns
- Error handling rules
- Anti-patterns to avoid
- Examples of correct usage

# PLAN
Phase 1: Define the trigger keywords and load condition
Phase 2: Write `references/conventions.md` for your target library
Phase 3: Test by asking the agent to review a code snippet
Phase 4: Iterate on conventions based on false positives/negatives

# TASKS
- [ ] Identify the library/framework this skill wraps
- [ ] Define trigger keywords (library name, file extensions, import patterns)
- [ ] Create `references/conventions.md` with at least 10 rules
- [ ] Test with a correct code sample (agent should find no violations)
- [ ] Test with a code sample that violates 3 rules
- [ ] Verify agent cites specific rule numbers in findings

# AGENT
pattern: tool-wrapper
interaction: single-turn
load-on-trigger: true
references:
  - references/conventions.md
instructions: |
  You are an expert in [LIBRARY_NAME]. When the user asks about or shares code
  using this library:
  1. Load references/conventions.md
  2. Apply every rule to the user's code or question
  3. For each violation: cite the rule, explain why it matters, show the fix
  4. For new code: follow every convention exactly
